phisticated theoretical exploration of how subjectivities are forged in the face of moral assessments and demands.Across the globe, ultrasonography and other technologies for prenatal screening offer prospective parents new information and present them with agonizing decisions never faced in the past. For anthropologists, this diagnostic capability raises important questions about individuality and collectivity, responsibility and choice. Arguing for more sustained anthropological attention to human quests for belonging, Haunting Images addresses existential questions of love and loss that concern us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAbortionxMoral and ethical aspectszVietnam. 0aAbortionxSocial aspectszVietnam. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aabnormal.  ababies.  abelonging.  abiology.  abiomedical technology.  acase studies.  achildren.  acontemporary vietnam.  adiagnostic capability.  aethnographic fieldwork.  afetus.  agender studies.  aglobal medicine.  ahanoi.  akinship.  alove and loss.  amedical innovations.  amoral assessments.  amorality.  amotherhood.  aparenthood.  apolitical.  apregnancy.  apregnant women.  aprenatal screening.  aprospective parents.  aquestions of belonging.  areproductive decision making.  atechnology.  aultrasonography.  aultrasound examination.  avietnam.  avietnamese mothers.  avietnamese women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027843140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095815940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958159/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 